text.tspan: The mole concept can be related to something you are probably more familiar with. If you are counting
eggs, you can have one egg, two eggs, ve eggs, ten eggs. You can keep counting to an innite number
of eggs. But think about this: What do you call a group of twelve eggs? This is often called a dozen.
Just like it is commonly known that one dozen contains twelve entities, we can quantify one mole of
particles as 6.022
particles.
Let’s try counting particles instead of eggs. Imagine a sample of pure water. You can have one
molecule, two molecules, increase that to hundreds of molecules and millions of molecules. Imagine
counting until you get to exactly 6.022
molecules. At that point, you have counted out one mole
of molecules.
Why do chemists use the mole unit?
When analyzing chemicals and chemical reactions, chemists are mainly concerned with the number of
elements, atoms, molecules or ions that are involved because, after all, it is the number of each type of
particles that is conserved in any physical or chemical transformation of matter.
